[1]
Date: Sun 20 Mar 2005
From: Cat Bachman <seamaid@optonline.net>
Source: Thanhnien Nes online, Sun 20 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://www.thanhniennews.com/healthy/?catid=8&newsid=5663>

Viet Nam: 2 children in central province test positive for avian influenza
-----------------------------------------------
A commune in central Viet Nam has been severely hit by avian influenza,
with 195 patients showing symptoms and 2 children testing positive with the
virus, reported a top provincial official. 2 siblings from the province's
Chau Hoa commune of Quang Binh province had tested positive for the H5N1
strain of avian influenza [virus], said Mai Xuan Thu, vice chairman of the
provincial People's Committee, on Sun 20 Mar 2005. The older sister, aged
13, died from [avian influenza virus infection] on 9 Mar 2005, while the
brother, aged 5, is in serious condition at the Hue Central Hospital. [The
following 2 reports indicate that diagnostic samples were not taken from
the elder sister, presumed to have died of avian influenza virus infection.
- Mod.CP]
Meanwhile, there are 195 other local residents who have shown symptoms of
the flu, said Ms. Thu. It is not yet clear whether these people, some of
whom had reportedly eaten sick chickens, have the symptoms of the deadly
bird flu or normal influenza. Of the 195 patients showing symptoms, 108 are
from Kinh Chau village, while the rest live in other villages in Chau Hoa
commune.
The outbreak hit the province's Kinh Chau village in Chau Hoa commune just
ahead of the Lunar New Year holidays, which started on 9 Feb 2005. The
province is currently trying to stop the spread of the influenza by culling
all poultry in the commune.
[Byline: Tung Lam, translated by Minh Phat]
--
Cat Bachman
<seamaid@optonline.net>
[This report was also received independently from Terry Allen
<tallen@igc.org>. Although 2 siblings are reported to have tested positive
for avian influenza virus in this region of Central Province, this event
does not confirm the occurrence of person-to-person transmission of
infection. Infection from a common source remains a possibility. (The test
of the report is ambiguous and suggests that perhaps a younger sister has
not succumbed to the infection). Also, the cause of death of the elder
sister and the severe illness of the brother are not necessarily related,
in view of the prevalence of a so far undiagnosed outbreak of respiratory
infection in the general population of the area. Further information and
independent confirmation of the diagnosis are awaited. - Mod.CP]
