[3]
Date: Sun 20 Mar 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua New agency online, Fri 18 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-03/18/content_2712999.htm>

Viet Nam: new case of avian influenza virus infection
-----------------------------------------------
Specimens from a 5-year-old boy from Viet Nam's central Quang Binh province
have just tested positive to [the H5N1 serotype of avian influenza virus],
raising the total number infected in the country to 25 since mid-December
2004, the newspaper Saigon Liberation reported on Fri 18 Mar 2005. The
testing by the Institute of Tropical Diseases in Hanoi on 17 Mar 2005
showed that the boy from Tuyen Hoa district is infected with bird flu, the
paper quoted Hoang VanMin, head of the provincial Veterinary Bureau, as saying.
In late February 2005, the boy's family, who live in a bird flu-hit area,
slaughtered a chicken given by one of their relatives for meal, and several
days later, the family's 3 children suffered a sudden illness, he said. One
day after being admitted to a hospital in Quang Binh, the boy's 13-year-old
sister died. Now, the boy is receiving treatment at a hospital in the
neighboring city of Hue after being hospitalized on 15 May 2005.
On 17 Mar 2005, a person from Quang Binh's Quang Trach district was
admitted to a hospital in the district with the bird flu symptoms of fever
and breathing difficulty, Min said. A total of 25 local people have been
reported to have contracted H5N1 since mid-December 2004, of whom 13 have died.
Avian influenza, which has killed and led to the forced culling of over 1.5
million fowl in 35 cities and provinces in Viet Nam since January 2005, is
cooling down, as 24 out of the 35 localities have detected no new affected
spots for at least 3 weeks so far, according to the Department of Animal
Health.
